BicycleExchange — Table Relationship Description

1. users (Central Hub)
users is the most connected table in the schema. Almost every table references it directly.

users → wallet (1:1) — Each user owns exactly one wallet. wallet.user_id is UNIQUE, enforcing the one-to-one constraint.
users → bike_listing (1:N) — A user acting as a seller can post many listings. bike_listing.seller_id → users.user_id.
users → events (1:N) — An admin user can create many events. events.create_by → users.user_id.
users → event_bicycle (1:N) — A seller registers their bicycles into events. event_bicycle.user_id → users.user_id.
users → event_inspector (1:N) — An inspector user can be assigned to many events. event_inspector.user_id → users.user_id.
users → reservation (1:N, twice) — A user appears as buyer_id (buyer side) and as inspector_id (assigned inspector) in the same reservation table.
users → check_in (1:N, twice) — A user appears as both buyer_id and seller_id in the check-in record.
users → transaction (1:N, twice) — A user appears as both buyer_id and seller_id in a transaction.
users → deposit (1:N) — A buyer user makes deposits. deposit.user_id → users.user_id.
users → dispute (1:N, twice) — A user can raise a dispute (raised_by) and also be the assigned inspector (assigned_inspector_id).
users → inspection_report (1:N) — An inspector submits reports. inspection_report.inspector_id → users.user_id.
users → wishlist (1:N) — A user can save many listings to their wishlist.


2. Bicycle Catalog Group

brand → bicycle (1:N) — A brand can have many bicycles. bicycle.brand_id → brand.brand_id.
category → bicycle (1:N) — A category classifies many bicycles. bicycle.category_id → category.category_id.
brand → bicycle_library (1:N) — A brand also appears in the reference library. bicycle_library.brand_id → brand.brand_id.
category → bicycle_library (1:N) — A category also classifies library entries. bicycle_library.category_id → category.category_id.
bicycle → bike_listing (1:1) — One bicycle asset backs exactly one listing. bike_listing.bicycle_id is UNIQUE.
bicycle → event_bicycle (1:N) — The same physical bicycle can be registered in multiple events over time. event_bicycle.bike_id → bicycle.bike_id.


bicycle_library is a standalone reference/lookup table — it does not participate in the transaction lifecycle. It exists purely to help users auto-fill bicycle specs when creating listings.


3. Listing & Wishlist Group

bike_listing → wishlist (1:N) — A listing can be saved by many users. wishlist.listing_id → bike_listing.listing_id.
bike_listing → reservation (1:N) — A listing can receive multiple reservation requests (though only one should be active at a time). reservation.listing_id → bike_listing.listing_id.
bike_listing → deposit (1:N) — Deposits are tied to a listing for non-event purchases. deposit.listing_id → bike_listing.listing_id.
bike_listing → event_bicycle (1:N) — A listing can be brought into multiple events. event_bicycle.listing_id → bike_listing.listing_id.
bike_listing → check_in (1:N) — Check-in records reference the listing being transacted. check_in.listing_id → bike_listing.listing_id.
bike_listing → transaction (1:N) — Completed transactions reference the original listing. transaction.listing_id → bike_listing.listing_id.


4. Events Group

events → event_bicycle (1:N) — An event hosts many bicycles registered by sellers. event_bicycle.event_id → events.event_id.
events → event_inspector (1:N) — An event has multiple inspectors assigned to it. event_inspector.event_id → events.event_id.
events → transaction (1:N) — Transactions completed at an event reference the event. transaction.event_id → events.event_id.
event_bicycle → reservation (1:N) — A bicycle at an event can be reserved by a buyer. reservation.event_bike_id → event_bicycle.event_bike_id.
event_bicycle → deposit (1:N) — Deposits for event bicycles reference event_bicycle. deposit.event_bike_id → event_bicycle.event_bike_id.
event_bicycle → check_in (1:N) — Check-ins can be linked to an event bicycle. check_in.event_bike_id → event_bicycle.event_bike_id.
event_bicycle → transaction (1:N) — Event-based transactions reference the event bicycle. transaction.event_bike_id → event_bicycle.event_bike_id.


5. Transaction Lifecycle (Core Flow)
This is the most critical chain in the entire schema. A sale flows through these tables in order:
bike_listing / event_bicycle
        ↓
     deposit  ←── created when buyer expresses intent
        ↓
   reservation ←── confirmed meeting between buyer & seller
        ↓
    check_in   ←── both parties physically meet
        ↓
  transaction  ←── sale is finalized
        ↓
    dispute    ←── (optional) raised if something goes wrong
        ↓
inspection_report ←── (optional) inspector evaluates the case
Detailed relationships:

deposit → reservation (1:1) — A deposit is linked to exactly one reservation. reservation.deposit_id is UNIQUE.
deposit → transaction (1:1) — A deposit is consumed by exactly one transaction. transaction.deposit_id is UNIQUE.
reservation → transaction (1:1) — Each completed reservation produces exactly one transaction. transaction.reservation_id is UNIQUE.
reservation → check_in (1:N) — A reservation can have check-in records associated with it.
reservation → inspection_report (1:N) — An inspector can file reports against a reservation.
transaction → dispute (1:1) — A transaction can have at most one dispute raised against it. dispute.transaction_id is UNIQUE.
dispute → inspection_report (1:1) — A dispute can have one inspection report resolving it. inspection_report.dispute_id is UNIQUE.


6. Wallet Group

users → wallet (1:1) — Strictly one wallet per user.
wallet → wallet_transaction (1:N) — Every balance change (top-up, withdrawal, fee, refund) is recorded as a wallet_transaction. wallet_transaction.wallet_id → wallet.wallet_id.


7. Platform Management (Standalone Tables)

system_config — No foreign keys in or out. Stores global platform settings like deposit percentage rates, service fee rates, etc. Read-only by the application at runtime.
invalidate_token — No foreign keys. Stores revoked JWT tokens as a blacklist. The application checks this table on every authenticated request.


