Field-Level Data Dictionary
Describes the purpose and function of every field in all 20 tables  |  March 2026

Introduction
This document provides a field-level data dictionary for the BicycleExchange database. For each of the 20 tables, every column is documented with its data type, key/constraint status, and a detailed description of its business function — what it stores, why it exists, and how it is used by the application.

Group 1: User & Authentication
1. users
Central user account table. Every actor on the platform — buyer, seller, inspector, and admin — has a record here. The role field determines what actions a user is permitted to perform.

Field Name	Data Type	Key / Constraint	Field Function & Description
user_id	integer	PK	Auto-incremented unique identifier for each user. Used as the primary reference key across all tables that involve a user.
username	varchar		The unique login handle chosen by the user. Used for authentication and display purposes.
password	varchar		Stores the bcrypt-hashed password. Never stored in plain text. Used during credential-based login.
full_name	varchar		The user's real full name as registered. Displayed on listings, reservations, and check-in records.
phone	varchar		Contact phone number. Used for buyer-seller communication coordination and check-in verification.
email	varchar		Email address used for account registration, notifications, and password recovery.
role	varchar		Defines the user's permission level on the platform. Accepted values: BUYER, SELLER, INSPECTOR, ADMIN. Controls what features and endpoints the user can access.
status	varchar		Current account status. Accepted values: ACTIVE (normal), INACTIVE (self-deactivated), BANNED (admin-suspended). Controls login eligibility.
address	varchar		Physical address of the user. Used for profile display and optionally for logistics.
avatar	varchar		URL pointing to the user's profile picture stored in object storage. Displayed throughout the UI.
google_id	varchar		Google OAuth2 subject ID. Populated when user registers or logs in via Google Sign-In. NULL for credential-only accounts.
created_at	date		Date the account was first created. Used for analytics and audit purposes.
create_date	date		Alternative creation date field. May reflect the date the profile was completed as opposed to initial registration.

2. wallet
Each user has exactly one wallet record. The wallet holds the user's platform balance which is used to pay deposits, receive sale proceeds, and pay/receive refunds.

Field Name	Data Type	Key / Constraint	Field Function & Description
wallet_id	integer	PK	Unique identifier for the wallet record.
balance	double	NOT NULL	Current available balance in VND. Updated atomically whenever a wallet_transaction is recorded. This is the authoritative balance figure.
username	varchar		Denormalized copy of the owner's username. Stored here for fast display without joining to users.
type	varchar		Wallet type indicator. Distinguishes between USER wallets and the platform's own SYSTEM wallet used to hold service fees.
updated_at	timestamp		Timestamp of the last balance change. Used to detect stale data and for audit trails.
user_id	integer	FK, UNIQUE	References users.user_id. The UNIQUE constraint enforces the 1-to-1 relationship — each user can have only one wallet.

3. wallet_transaction
Immutable ledger of every balance movement in every wallet. Each row represents one atomic change — a top-up, withdrawal, fee deduction, refund, or transfer. The running balance is stored for quick balance reconstruction.

Field Name	Data Type	Key / Constraint	Field Function & Description
wallet_trans_id	integer	PK	Unique identifier for the ledger entry.
amount	double	NOT NULL	The monetary amount involved in this transaction (VND). Always a positive number; the type field determines direction.
type	varchar		Direction and reason for the balance change. Values: DEPOSIT (top-up), WITHDRAWAL, REFUND, FEE (platform fee deducted), TRANSFER (peer payment).
description	varchar		Human-readable explanation of this entry, e.g. 'Deposit for listing #42' or 'Platform fee for sale #7'.
balance	double		Wallet balance immediately after this transaction was applied. Enables balance reconstruction without summing all rows.
create_at	timestamp		Exact timestamp this entry was created. Used for chronological ledger display and auditing.
wallet_id	integer	FK	References wallet.wallet_id. Identifies which wallet this entry belongs to.

4. invalidate_token
JWT token blacklist. When a user logs out or a token is revoked, the token string is inserted here. The authentication middleware checks this table on every request to reject invalidated tokens before they naturally expire.

Field Name	Data Type	Key / Constraint	Field Function & Description
id	varchar	PK	The raw JWT token string used as the primary key. Allows O(1) lookup by the auth middleware to determine if a token has been revoked.
expiry_date	timestamp		The token's original expiry timestamp. A background cleanup job uses this to purge rows that are already past expiry, keeping the table small.

